<p id="mwAZ4">Faraday's books, with the exception of <i id="mwAZ8">Chemical Manipulation</i>, were collections of scientific papers or transcriptions of lectures.<sup about="#mwt240" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-84" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-84"}}'><a href="./Michael_Faraday#cite_note-84" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 84;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[84]</span></a></sup>  Since his death, Faraday's diary has been published, as have several large volumes of his letters and Faraday's journal from his travels with Davy in 1813–1815.</p>
